Note:
Linux x86_64 Syscall Platform - Primary Compilation Target

Defines all Linux x86_64 (AMD64) system call numbers, platform metadata, and
registration logic for the Runa compiler's syscall subsystem. This is the
highest-priority platform file as it targets WSL and native Linux x86_64 hosts.

System call numbers correspond to the Linux kernel's arch/x86/entry/syscalls/syscall_64.tbl
for the x86_64 architecture. The System V AMD64 ABI is used for the calling convention:
- RAX holds the syscall number
- Arguments passed in RDI, RSI, RDX, R10, R8, R9 (up to 6 arguments)
- Return value in RAX (negative values indicate errno)
- RCX and R11 are clobbered by the syscall instruction

This file provides:
1. All Linux x86_64 syscall number constants used by the compiler
2. Platform info creation for Linux x86_64
3. Full syscall registration with argument types and categories
4. Fast name-to-number lookup without requiring a registry instance
:End Note

Import "compiler/backend/syscalls/platforms/platform_interface.runa" as PlatformInterface
Import "compiler/backend/syscalls/syscall_registry.runa" as SyscallRegistry
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Linux x86_64 Syscall Number Constants
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Syscall numbers are taken directly from the Linux kernel source:
arch/x86/entry/syscalls/syscall_64.tbl

These are the stable ABI numbers for the x86_64 architecture. They do not change
between kernel versions (new syscalls are only added, never renumbered). Each
constant maps a human-readable name to the numeric value the kernel expects in RAX
when the "syscall" instruction is executed.

The selection covers all syscalls needed by the Runa runtime and standard library:
file I/O, memory management, process control, networking, signal handling, time,
and filesystem operations.
@End Reasoning

Note: --- File I/O Syscalls ---
Constant SYS_READ as Integer is 0
Constant SYS_WRITE as Integer is 1
Constant SYS_OPEN as Integer is 2
Constant SYS_CLOSE as Integer is 3
Constant SYS_STAT as Integer is 4
Constant SYS_FSTAT as Integer is 5
Constant SYS_LSTAT as Integer is 6
Constant SYS_POLL as Integer is 7
Constant SYS_LSEEK as Integer is 8
Constant SYS_IOCTL as Integer is 16
Constant SYS_ACCESS as Integer is 21
Constant SYS_PIPE as Integer is 22
Constant SYS_DUP as Integer is 32
Constant SYS_DUP2 as Integer is 33
Constant SYS_FCNTL as Integer is 72
Constant SYS_FTRUNCATE as Integer is 77
Constant SYS_GETDENTS as Integer is 78
Constant SYS_GETCWD as Integer is 79
Constant SYS_RENAME as Integer is 82
Constant SYS_UNLINK as Integer is 87
Constant SYS_CHMOD as Integer is 90

Note: --- Newer File I/O Syscalls (AT-family, preferred over legacy) ---
Constant SYS_OPENAT as Integer is 257
Constant SYS_MKDIRAT as Integer is 258
Constant SYS_FSTATAT as Integer is 262
Constant SYS_UNLINKAT as Integer is 263
Constant SYS_RENAMEAT as Integer is 264

Note: --- Memory Management Syscalls ---
Constant SYS_MMAP as Integer is 9
Constant SYS_MPROTECT as Integer is 10
Constant SYS_MUNMAP as Integer is 11
Constant SYS_BRK as Integer is 12

