Note: --- Miscellaneous Syscalls ---
Constant SYS_GETRANDOM as Integer is 318

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Total syscall count for registration validation
Note: ============================================================================
Constant LINUX_X86_64_SYSCALL_COUNT as Integer is 58

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Platform Info Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Creates the PlatformInfo descriptor for Linux x86_64. This struct is registered
with the syscall registry and used by the code generator to determine:
- Pointer size (8 bytes for 64-bit addressing)
- Endianness (little-endian on x86_64)
- Syscall instruction ("syscall" opcode)
- ABI name ("System V AMD64" - the standard Linux x86_64 calling convention)

The platform_id of 1 (PLATFORM_LINUX_X86_64) is the primary target for
WSL development and native Linux deployment.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_linux_x86_64_platform_info" returns Integer:
    Note: Creates and returns a PlatformInfo struct for Linux x86_64
    Note: Returns pointer to PlatformInfo, or 0 on allocation failure

    Let info be PlatformInterface.create_platform_info(PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_X86_64, MachineCode.TARGET_ARCH_X86_64, MachineCode.TARGET_OS_LINUX, 8, PlatformInterface.ENDIAN_LITTLE)
    If info is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    PlatformInterface.platform_info_set_name(info, "Linux x86_64")
    PlatformInterface.platform_info_set_abi(info, "System V AMD64")

    Return info
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Syscall Registration
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Registers all Linux x86_64 syscall definitions with the central registry. This is
called during compiler initialization to populate the registry with every syscall
the compiler and runtime might need to emit.

Each syscall definition includes:
- The kernel syscall number (from the constants above)
- The canonical name (used for cross-platform abstract references)
- The argument count (0-6 for x86_64 syscalls)
- Per-argument type classification (FD, PTR, SIZE, FLAGS, etc.)
- The functional category (FILE_IO, MEMORY, PROCESS, NETWORK, TIME, SIGNAL)
- The noreturn flag (for exit and exit_group)

The type classifications enable the compiler to:
1. Validate argument types at compile time
2. Emit appropriate register sizing and sign extension
3. Generate better error messages for incorrect syscall usage
4. Support security auditing by categorizing syscall usage

Registration order does not matter; all syscalls are stored in dictionary
structures keyed by both name and number for O(1) lookup.
@End Reasoning

Process called "register_linux_x86_64_syscalls" that takes registry as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Registers all Linux x86_64 syscall definitions with the given registry
    Note: Returns 1 on success, 0 on failure

    If registry is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create and register the platform info
    Let platform_info be create_linux_x86_64_platform_info()
    If platform_info is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let reg_result be SyscallRegistry.registry_register_platform(registry, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_X86_64, platform_info)
    If reg_result is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create and register the syscall calling convention
    Let convention be PlatformInterface.create_syscall_convention(PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_X86_64)
    If convention is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let conv_result be SyscallRegistry.register_convention(registry, PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_X86_64, convention)
    If conv_result is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Local alias for the platform ID to reduce verbosity
    Let pid be PlatformInterface.PLATFORM_LINUX_X86_64

    Note: ====================================================================
    Note: FILE I/O SYSCALLS
    Note: ====================================================================

    Note: --- read(fd, buf, count) -> ssize_t ---
    Let def_read be PlatformInterface.create_syscall_definition(SYS_READ, "read", 3, PlatformInterface.SYSCALL_CAT_FILE_IO, pid)
    PlatformInterface.syscall_def_set_arg_type(def_read, 0, PlatformInterface.SYSCALL_ARG_FD)
    PlatformInterface.syscall_def_set_arg_type(def_read, 1, PlatformInterface.SYSCALL_ARG_PTR)
    PlatformInterface.syscall_def_set_arg_type(def_read, 2, PlatformInterface.SYSCALL_ARG_SIZE)
    SyscallRegistry.register_syscall(registry, pid, def_read)

    Note: --- write(fd, buf, count) -> ssize_t ---
    Let def_write be PlatformInterface.create_syscall_definition(SYS_WRITE, "write", 3, PlatformInterface.SYSCALL_CAT_FILE_IO, pid)
    PlatformInterface.syscall_def_set_arg_type(def_write, 0, PlatformInterface.SYSCALL_ARG_FD)
    PlatformInterface.syscall_def_set_arg_type(def_write, 1, PlatformInterface.SYSCALL_ARG_PTR)
    PlatformInterface.syscall_def_set_arg_type(def_write, 2, PlatformInterface.SYSCALL_ARG_SIZE)
    SyscallRegistry.register_syscall(registry, pid, def_write)

    Note: --- open(pathname, flags, mode) -> fd ---
